  ./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:52:4. Check dynamic-access coverage across versions.
  ./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:54:   - Compare `dynamicAccess.coverageRatio`, `coveredCalls`, `totalCalls`, and the `dynamicAccess.breakdown` entries for reflection, resources, proxies, serialization, JNI, or any other present report type.
  ./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:55:   - Do not use `user-code-filter.json`, agent configuration, or metadata file contents to argue that the reported dynamic-access values are not comparable. Use the stats values as reported unless the stats are missing or stale.
  ./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:56:   - A lower `coverageRatio` or lower `coveredCalls` for the new version is blocking unless the total dynamic-access surface changed and the PR explains why the reduction is expected.
  ./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:57:   - If `totalCalls` increases while `coveredCalls` stays flat or the ratio drops, ask for additional test coverage or metadata unless the uncovered calls are clearly outside the library behavior under test.
  ./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:64:   - Do not require an exact match. Differences are normal when upstream APIs move, generated metadata is cleaned up, or dynamic-access totals change.
  ./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:66:   - When the new total is below 25% of the original and the tests and dynamic-access stats still claim comparable coverage, ask for restored metadata or a concrete explanation of the API/package change.
  ./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:103:- For coverage drops: say that dynamic-access coverage must not regress between tested versions, cite the old and new values, and ask for either restored coverage or a concrete explanation.
